{
  "text": "\ue062is study utilizes historical records to reconstruct past events and thus can be classi\ufffded as retrospective longitudinal research-an approach that has been considered as a practical alternative to the costly and inefficient panel-based longitudinal research [CITATION_1] . I selected Dragon Villas, a gated community in northeast Beijing, as the \ufffdeld site because of its long history and its presence of contacts. Evidence was primarily drawn from documents collected over eighteen years (1994) (1995) (1996) (1997) (1998) (1999) (2000) (2001) (2002) (2003) (2004) (2005) (2006) (2007) (2008) (2009) (2010) (2011) (2012) , including records of homeowners and tenants, meeting agendas, management expenditure statements, and internal memoranda of the management company. I also conducted twelve interviews between June and July 2012 with a diverse group of people that included the developer, the property manager, and several HOA members. \ue062e paper begins with a discussion on relevant government regulations in Beijing that constitutes the macrobackground of the case study. \ue062is discussion is followed by three sections that describe the case study. In each section, I demonstrate how a longitudinal perspective can reveal new insights. \ue062e \ufffdrst section examines the drivers of neighborhood democracy. \ue062e second section investigates the process of neighborhood democratization. \ue062e third section discusses the impact of neighborhood democracy. \ue062e paper concludes with a re\ufffdection on the strengths and weaknesses of a longitudinal approach.",
